Two birds seen, photographed, and recorded. Associating closely with a third bird I was not able to positively ID as it dove down to the undergrowth too quickly to get a good viewing, but certainly another chickadee of some kind. Heard calling repeatedly and briefly singing, much raspier voice than BCCH or CBCH. Shortly after arriving at the pin on the RBA I heard the raspy calls coming from high in the conifers closer towards the intersection of the two trails. To my delight the birds dove down into the bushes low beside the trail where I was able to photograph them quickly before they disappeared down into the undergrowth. Nuthatches and BCCH and CBCH also heard nearby. Visually different from a BCCH due to the bold white eyebrow streaking through the dark cap. Back of camera photo to be added along with the checklist. Audio recording and full quality photo will be added when I get back to my house on the island later this week.

Locality: Crater Lake NP--KBO Munson Valley Banding Station
Observation Details: One juvenile banded. Confirmed as Sierra ssp by plumage features in-hand. This bird also had additional white/leucistic feathers in crown.  Additional notes from Alex: I usually refrain from using the Sierra Nevada and Rocky Mtns subspecies-group designations for MOCH because I don't really consider them field-identifiable, with (as far as I can tell) complete overlap in plumage features (throughout the year and by age) and vocals. Pacific birds (it seems) eBird lumps as Sierra Nevada. Pacific birds average smaller in wing chord and tail length than Rocky Mtns birds. Since we had this bird in the hand I figured it was a good opportunity to try and determine subspecies using Pyle's descriptions. I wouldn't be surprised if eBird does away with these designations, but who knows...   Anyway, according to Pyle the expected subspecies at Crater would be baileyae (or "abbreviatus" more specifically). Our bird's wing chord was nicely in the range given for this subspecies, and at the extreme low end for gambelli. The lack of any olive color in the mantle, wing coverts, or flanks also point away from gambelli... our bird has a light gray mantle with no olive color, and its flanks are ever-so-slightly buffy.   With plumage favoring baileyae/abbreviatus, and given its location as a juvenile bird on the breeding grounds for baileyae/abbreviatus, I think this is a good representative for what eBird would describe as a Sierra Nevada bird.

Found by Kaiyote Snow at 2:30 pm in small shore pines along Olympic Discovery Trail, near administrative offices for McKinley Mill (formerly Nippon Mill). Actively feeding on pine seeds pulled from cones.  Classic MOCH, very gray wings above, and gray breast and belly below, with no hint of buffy or brown. Prominant white supercilium circling around to rear sides of head but not all the way to nape, with black mask through eye circling around to nape. Top view down on head resembles RB Nuthatch.  White superciliaries extends forward on each side to almost meet above the bill. Narrow black chin and throat contrasts with big white cheeks. May be molting tail feathers.  Carolyn recorded call notes - scratchy hoarse notes.  Thanks Kaiyote of kaiyotetours.com, who knows MOCH from her time in Rocky Mountain National Park!

Observation Details: Two birds seen, photographed, and recorded. Associating closely with a third bird I was not able to positively ID as it dove down to the undergrowth too quickly to get a good viewing, but certainly another chickadee of some kind. Heard calling repeatedly and briefly singing, much raspier voice than BCCH or CBCH. Shortly after arriving at the pin on the RBA I heard the raspy calls coming from high in the conifers closer towards the intersection of the two trails. To my delight the birds dove down into the bushes low beside the trail where I was able to photograph them quickly before they disappeared down into the undergrowth. Nuthatches and BCCH and CBCH also heard nearby. Visually different from a BCCH due to the bold white eyebrow streaking through the dark cap. Back of camera photo to be added along with the checklist. Audio recording and full quality photo will be added when I get back to my house on the island later this week.

Locality: Crater Lake NP--KBO Munson Valley Banding Station
Observation Details: One juvenile banded. Confirmed as Sierra ssp by plumage features in-hand. This bird also had additional white/leucistic feathers in crown.  Additional notes from Alex: I usually refrain from using the Sierra Nevada and Rocky Mtns subspecies-group designations for MOCH because I don't really consider them field-identifiable, with (as far as I can tell) complete overlap in plumage features (throughout the year and by age) and vocals. Pacific birds (it seems) eBird lumps as Sierra Nevada. Pacific birds average smaller in wing chord and tail length than Rocky Mtns birds. Since we had this bird in the hand I figured it was a good opportunity to try and determine subspecies using Pyle's descriptions. I wouldn't be surprised if eBird does away with these designations, but who knows...   Anyway, according to Pyle the expected subspecies at Crater would be baileyae (or "abbreviatus" more specifically). Our bird's wing chord was nicely in the range given for this subspecies, and at the extreme low end for gambelli. The lack of any olive color in the mantle, wing coverts, or flanks also point away from gambelli... our bird has a light gray mantle with no olive color, and its flanks are ever-so-slightly buffy.   With plumage favoring baileyae/abbreviatus, and given its location as a juvenile bird on the breeding grounds for baileyae/abbreviatus, I think this is a good representative for what eBird would describe as a Sierra Nevada bird.

Media notes: Photo demonstrates 1) worn MOCH can resemble MOCH x BCCH and 2) reflected light can cause a chickadees undersides to have a buff wash

Observation Details: Bird actively feeding in Huge Douglass Fir in sunny side lower branches in a flock of mostly Townend's Warblers, kinglets, and bushtits. A few Black-capped Chickadees were nearby but not (at the time) intimate with the "winter flock".  Bigger and whiter than the regular BCCHs, much! whiter in general with a broad! white cheek patch; thin black eye stripe, white supercilium and narrow black crown. It was mostly foraging on inner boughs but would flash to an outer position once in a while for a quick look. Peter James and Becky Riley got good looks also, as the bird was in that tree from about 1:30-3:00p. The picture is of a picture Tim Fox took in the same tree yesterday, 12/07: Very likely the same bird. I vaguely remember Tim saw the bird with me today, but the bird never offered up a suitable photo op for him; hence the use of yesterday image.       IMAGE  BY  TIM FOX

Observation Details: One juvenile banded. Confirmed as Sierra ssp by plumage features in-hand. This bird also had additional white/leucistic feathers in crown.  Additional notes from Alex: I usually refrain from using the Sierra Nevada and Rocky Mtns subspecies-group designations for MOCH because I don't really consider them field-identifiable, with (as far as I can tell) complete overlap in plumage features (throughout the year and by age) and vocals. Pacific birds (it seems) eBird lumps as Sierra Nevada. Pacific birds average smaller in wing chord and tail length than Rocky Mtns birds. Since we had this bird in the hand I figured it was a good opportunity to try and determine subspecies using Pyle's descriptions. I wouldn't be surprised if eBird does away with these designations, but who knows...   Anyway, according to Pyle the expected subspecies at Crater would be baileyae (or "abbreviatus" more specifically). Our bird's wing chord was nicely in the range given for this subspecies, and at the extreme low end for gambelli. The lack of any olive color in the mantle, wing coverts, or flanks also point away from gambelli... our bird has a light gray mantle with no olive color, and its flanks are ever-so-slightly buffy.   With plumage favoring baileyae/abbreviatus, and given its location as a juvenile bird on the breeding grounds for baileyae/abbreviatus, I think this is a good representative for what eBird would describe as a Sierra Nevada bird.

When I first approached the stairs to Sherrard Point this morning I heard a raspy chickadee in the canopy, but since I hadn't heard a MOCH in a while I thought of it as an aberrant CBCH and immediately discounted the idea of MOCH and didn't record it. During my time at the top a couple CBCH worked there way through the firs calling and subsequently I reconsidered what I heard hours earlier. Sometime after that I finally heard the raspy calls again in the firs seemingly moving closer and closer to the viewpoint. I immediately started recording on my phone with my camera ready and it soon popped out at the nearest trees. As I shot photos rapid-fire I focused on finding and noticed the clean white supercilium as well as the grayish sides and flanks and also seeing the darker gray back and black cap with the black line through the eye. It continued mucking around near the point and eventually went back from where it came. I did not see it fly off. Later on Ross rushed up to the viewpoint after finishing leading his Audubon Field Trip and while out of breath mentioned he just had 4 MOCH near the bathrooms 30-60 mins prior. They seemed to have been moving through!

Observation Details: Have had 2 mountain chickadees coming to the feeders so decided to check my bird box and there was a nest!  Couldn't see anything because the fluff was so high so clicked a quick photo and before I could get out of there the chickadee was in the nearby juniper scolding.

Chickadee with black crown, black throat,  white cheeks, and tiny bill was observed foraging in pine tree. A white supercilium was observed indicating mountain chickadee. I was very surprised to see this species at this location, especially in May. Mountain chickadees are rare in central and southern coastal county locations. This is the first time I've seen this species at this patch location.
Conservative count; vocals indicate probably more.

Still audible as of 1800.  Update on 10/24 changing count from 2 to 3 after confirming 4 in the flock today.

Two birds seen, photographed, and recorded. Associating closely with a third bird I was not able to positively ID as it dove down to the undergrowth too quickly to get a good viewing, but certainly another chickadee of some kind. Heard calling repeatedly and briefly singing, much raspier voice than BCCH or CBCH. Shortly after arriving at the pin on the RBA I heard the raspy calls coming from high in the conifers closer towards the intersection of the two trails. To my delight the birds dove down into the bushes low beside the trail where I was able to photograph them quickly before they disappeared down into the undergrowth. Nuthatches and BCCH and CBCH also heard nearby. Visually different from a BCCH due to the bold white eyebrow streaking through the dark cap. Back of camera photo to be added along with the checklist. Audio recording and full quality photo will be added when I get back to my house on the island later this week.

Observation Details: All 3 species of chickadee were feeding at the same time.  The Black-Capped and Chestnut-Backed prefer the feeders, but the Mountain Chickadee was feeding on the ground under and beside the pole feeder.  The nuthatches and chickadees take seeds from the tube feeder and drop the ones they don't want on the ground, so he was pecking at those and fir cones/samara that had dropped on the ground.  The other birds will forage on the ground for a while, but the Mountain Chickadee swoops in from the neighboring elderberry tree, drops onto the ground, picks up a seed in 1-4 seconds, then flies off, so it's very difficult to get a photo of him.

Observation Details: I walked around the treatment plant looking for the bird that has been reported here and ran into a mixed flock on the north side in the line of trees adjacent to the treatment plant and just beyond the outfield fence of the ballfield. A Mountain Chickadee was the first bird I saw in this flock, and I began to suspect there was more than one after it seemed to teleport from one location to another! Eventually, I got a view of three Mountain Chickadees at the same time in the same tree. When I left they were on the west side of the plant along a trail that connects Benton Pl to the ballfields.

Observation Details: Hoarse nasally slow chickadee sounds. Heard a little before finally locating. At edge of camera range and too far for sound recording. Similar to BCCH but with white brows that go to back of head. I’ve observed this species in central Oregon, Rocky Mountains, and Whistler, B.C.. Sound was immediately recognizable. First for me in my home state. Flagged unreported/rare
not a lifer but my first up close

Two birds seen, photographed, and recorded. Associating closely with a third bird I was not able to positively ID as it dove down to the undergrowth too quickly to get a good viewing, but certainly another chickadee of some kind. Heard calling repeatedly and briefly singing, much raspier voice than BCCH or CBCH. Shortly after arriving at the pin on the RBA I heard the raspy calls coming from high in the conifers closer towards the intersection of the two trails. To my delight the birds dove down into the bushes low beside the trail where I was able to photograph them quickly before they disappeared down into the undergrowth. Nuthatches and BCCH and CBCH also heard nearby. Visually different from a BCCH due to the bold white eyebrow streaking through the dark cap. Back of camera photo to be added along with the checklist. Audio recording and full quality photo will be added when I get back to my house on the island later this week.
